","1105–Female":"1105–Overleden","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1101":"1101","about 1135":"circa 1135","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England"},"en":{"1105–":"1105–Deceased","1101–1136":"1101–1136","1135–1246":"1135–1246","1105–Female":"1105–Deceased","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1101":"1101","about 1135":"about 1135","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Dorset) and Irish (County Mayo): habitational name from Bingham (Nottinghamshire). The placename is probably from an Old English folk-name <i>Bynningas</i> (‘the people associated with a man named <i>Bynna</i>’), or possibly from an unattested Old English word <i>bing</i> ‘a kettle-shaped hollow’, + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’.","Irish (Ulster, of Scottish origin): altered form of   Bigham  .","American shortened and altered form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames such as   Bingenheimer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ingham","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from any of the places called Ingham, particularly in Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Suffolk. The placename is from the Old English personal name <i>Inga</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. In Yorkshire this name was sometimes confused with   Bingham   in the 18th century.","English (of Norman origin): variant of the obsolete Norman surname <i>Engaine</i>; see   Gain  ."]},{"name":"Bigham","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire) and Irish: habitational name from either Bigholm in Beith parish (Ayrshire) or Bigholms in Langholm parish (Dumfriesshire). The second element of the placename is from Older Scots <i>holm</i> (Old Norse <i>holmr</i>) ‘islet’, ‘raised land in a marsh’, ‘a stretch of low-lying land beside a river; a meadow’. The first element may be an unattested Older Scots <i>bigge</i>, a shortened form of <i>bigging</i> ‘building’. The name was taken to Ulster in the 17th and 18th centuries, where it was used interchangeably with   Bingham  ."]},{"name":"Bingenheimer","meanings":["German and Jewish (from Germany): habitational name for someone from Bingenheim on the Eder river (Hesse). Compare   Bingham  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":1,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705187,"age":110,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":119,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William de Bingham was born in 1105, in Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England. She had at least 1 son with William de Bingham."},"et":{"1105–":"1105–Surnud","1101–1136":"1101–1136","1135–1246":"1135–1246","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1101":"1101","about 1135":"umbes 1135","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1105–":"1105–Kuollut","1101–1136":"1101–1136","1135–1246":"1135–1246","1105–Female":"1105–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1101":"1101","about 1135":"noin 1135","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, 